# Workspace Index

AI-assisted development workspace for **{{.ProjectName}}**. Organized by **lifecycle** first (durable / in-flight / experimental), then by subject.

## Top-level map

| Folder | Lifecycle | What lives here |
|---|---|---|
| `knowledge/` | Durable. Curated. Read by agents. | Things that should still be true next sprint. |
| `work/` | In-flight. Per-initiative. | Plans, research, notes for an active branch or initiative. Archive when shipped. |
| `lab/` | Experimental. Often throwaway. | Executable scripts to probe APIs, capture flow, reproduce bugs. Promote learnings to `knowledge/`. |
| `tickets/` | External system mirror. | Issue tracker cache (e.g., Jira/Linear). |
| `decisions/` | Durable. Append-only. | Lightweight ADRs for one-way doors. |
| `journal/` | Time-series. | Daily/session notes. Cheap context for the next session. |

## `knowledge/` -- the slow-changing layer

| Subfolder | When to add to it |
|---|---|
| `domains/<flow>/` | A business flow we own. Each domain has the same shape: `overview.md`, `invariants.md`, `glossary.md`, `gotchas.md`, `key-files.md`. |
| `integrations/<vendor>/` | A third-party system we call. Our notes live at the root; raw vendor docs/postman collections live under `vendor/`. |
| `architecture/` | Cross-cutting: codemaps, infra, data model, auth model. Not tied to a single domain. |
| `engineering/` | Generic patterns and external research. Not project-specific. |

## `work/` -- the in-flight layer

Each initiative is a folder. Use `_template/` as the scaffold:

```
work/<slug>/
  README.md      status, PR/branch, owner, what + why
  research/      initial discovery
  plan/          specs, plans
  notes/         running learnings, audits
  artifacts/     screenshots, csv dumps, captured outputs
```

Move to `_archive/` when the initiative ships or is abandoned.

## `lab/` -- the experimental layer

Each experiment is a folder, not a loose script. Mirrors `knowledge/integrations/` where it makes sense:

```
lab/<vendor>/<experiment>/
  README.md      what this experiment proved (or didn't)
  script.py      latest version -- avoid v2/v3/v4 sprawl
  fixtures/
  runs/          captured outputs (rotate aggressively)
```

`lab/_scratch/` is for one-off pokes. Prune often.

## Conventions

- Lowercase, kebab-case paths.
- Every directory has a `README.md` (one paragraph: what's here, when to add to it).
- Time-bound files use ISO date prefixes (`YYYY-MM-DD-...`).
- Folders prefixed with `_` (`_template`, `_archive`, `_scratch`) are meta and sort to the bottom.
- Frontmatter on docs where useful: `status`, `domain`, `owner`, `updated`, `related-pr`.
